407238, -0.003402489935979247, 0.010031657293438911, 0.019842686131596565, 0.02075277455151081, 0.025661736726760864, -0.012031094171106815, -0.014002951793372631, -0.011451946571469307, 0.007880538702011108, 0.0019046359229832888, -0.024517232552170753, -0.019029121845960617, 0.010914167389273643, 0.01605065166950226, 0.043105099350214005, -0.056177280843257904, 0.005705289542675018, 0.017346838489174843, -0.02351061813533306, 0.023827770724892616, 0.026351198554039, 0.021759387105703354, 0.033121705055236816, -0.008494159206748009, -0.020421834662556648, 0.033342331647872925, -0.03450062498450279, -0.011886307038366795, 0.011941463686525822, -0.03543829172849655, -0.0170572642236948, -0.01871197111904621, 0.015761077404022217, -0.0004951191367581487, -0.007728857453912497, -0.009142252616584301, 0.03466609865427017]], "input": ["\"DEPRECIATION\":\"Depreciation is a method of allocating the cost of a tangible asset over its useful life. It is not a cash flow but an accounting method for past capital expenditure.\"", "\"UNCONTROLLABLE COSTS\":\"Uncontrollable costs are costs that cannot be influenced directly by the person in charge of the budget or cost center. Examples include management charges and reallocated non-production overheads.\"", "\"NOTIONAL COSTS\":\"Notional costs are hypothetical costs, such as recharges of head office costs or management charges, which do not increase as a result of the decision and are irrelevant.\"", "\"OPPORTUNITY COST\":\"Opportunity cost\" is the value of the next best alternative that is foregone when making a decision. It represents the cost of forgoing the next best option in favor of the chosen course of action. For instance, in the context of Division M, the opportunity cost is the lost contribution of $80 per unit when selling internally instead of externally. Similarly, for Push, the opportunity cost is the foregone sales proceeds of $3,000 when using a telephone system for a contract instead of selling it. Opportunity cost can also refer to the potential revenue from selling unused materials or the scrap value of materials not regularly used. It is a measure of the value of the benefit sacrificed when one course of action is chosen over another, highlighting the importance of considering the potential benefits of rejected alternatives. Lack of scarcity implies zero opportunity cost, as there would be no foregone alternatives.", "\"EXAMPLE OF OPPORTUNITY COST\":\"A company has been invited to tender for a contract to produce a component, R2D2. Production of R2D2 will require 100 hours of processing on Machine X. If Machine X is currently working at full capacity producing 50 units of Product Z an hour, each unit of Product Z makes a contribution of $2. If 100 hours of Machine X time is used to fulfill the new contract, the lost contribution of $10,000 (50 * $2 * 100) is an opportunity cost of producing R2D2 and should be taken into account when deciding how much to tender for the contract.\"", "\"MINIMUM PRICE\":\"The minimum price that makes a contract worthwhile is equal to the relevant cost. At this price, no profit or loss would be made on the contract.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST\":\"Relevant cost refers to the cost that will be affected by a decision. It is the cost that will change as a result of choosing one alternative over another. Relevant costs are future costs that will differ between alternatives.\"", "\"MATERIALS FOR ONE-OFF CONTRACT\":\"Guidance for determining the relevant cost of materials for a one-off contract includes considering whether the materials have already been acquired and whether they are used regularly in the business. If not acquired, the current market price is the relevant cost. If acquired and used regularly, the replacement cost is the relevant cost. If not used regularly, the opportunity cost, such as scrap value, is the relevant cost.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF RAW MATERIALS\":\"Crocus Co is considering making a new product that requires several types of raw material. The example details the relevant costs for materials A, B, and C based on their current purchase prices, inventory levels, and alternative uses.\"", "\"QUIZ: RELEVANT COSTS OF MATERIALS\":\"This quiz involves determining the relevant costs for materials required by Bob, a carpenter, to make a special dining room table. The materials include oak wood, varnish, and hinges, each with different considerations for relevant cost calculation.\"", "\"REPLACEMENT COST\":\"Replacement cost refers to the cost to replace an asset or material at its current market price. It is often used as the relevant cost when materials are regularly used in the business and need to be replenished.\"", "\"SCRAP VALUE\":\"Scrap value is the estimated residual value of an asset or material at the end of its useful life. It is considered as the relevant cost when materials are not used regularly and could be sold off instead of being used in a new project.\"", "\"CURRENT MARKET PRICE\":\"Current market price is the price at which an asset or material can be bought or sold in the market at the present time. It is used as the relevant cost for materials that have not yet been acquired for a one-off contract.\"", "\"INVENTORY LEVELS\":\"Inventory levels refer to the quantity of materials or products that a business has on hand. When determining relevant costs, inventory levels help assess whether existing materials can be used or if new materials need to be purchased.\"", "\"ALTERNATIVE USES\":\"Alternative uses refer to other potential applications or purposes for materials or resources. In relevant cost analysis, considering alternative uses helps determine the opportunity cost of using materials for a specific project.\"", "\"CROCUS CO\":\"Crocus Co is a hypothetical company used in an example to illustrate the relevant costs of raw materials for a new product. The example considers the current purchase prices, inventory levels, and alternative uses of materials A, B, and C.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}